# MyFavouriteAlbums for advanced users and developers 

## Prerequisites

Before you will be able to open MyFavouriteAlbums (MFA) in RStudio, you will need:

### R

1. Download and install the latest version of R [here](https://cran.r-project.org/mirrors.html). This will show a large list of ‘mirrors’ to choose from. Pick either ‘0-cloud’ at the top of the page, or a mirror from the closest geographical region.  
2. Pick a version appropriate for your operating system (MacOS, Windows, Linux).

### RStudio

1. Only after downloading and installing R, download the latest version of RStudio [here](https://posit.co/download/rstudio-desktop/).   
2. Pick a version appropriate for your operating system, and install.

### MyFavouriteAlbums

1. Go to the github repository [here](https://github.com/UW-Example-Student/MyFavoriteAlbums/tree/main).  
2. Click on the green ‘ \<\> Code’ dropdown and click “Download Zip”  
3. Extract the file into the desired  file location.   
4. Check that you have the full list of files:  
   ![][image1]

## Using MyFavouriteAlbums

![][image2]  
RStudio after being opened

Step 1: Install required RStudio packages

* There are 4 RStudio packages that will need to be installed for MFA to work.  
  * Shiny (allows MFA to be deployed in Shiny)  
  * dplyr (allows for statistical ‘commands’ like filtering, arranging)  
  * DT (allows data to be displayed as tables)  
  * ggplot2 (gives MFA graphing functionality)  
* To install an RStudio package, type *install.packages(“package\_name”)* into the RStudio console and press Enter. Make sure to install each package one-by-one.


Step 2: Opening MyFavouriteAlbums

* In RStudio, go to *File* \-\> *Open File*  
* Navigate to the MyFavouriteAlbums folder  
* Select ‘app’ and click *Open*. A new window will pop up.

Step 3: Running MyFavouriteAlbums

* With MFA open in RStudio, click on *Run App* to the top right  
  of the new window.  
* The application will start and should automatically open in a new RStudio window. You also have the option in the new window to open it in your web browser by clicking *open in browser*, located in the top left corner

## Creating your own album entries for MyFavouriteAlbums

This section will walk you through creating your own album entries for MyFavouriteAlbums to analyse. We will be adding Ryo Fukui’s 1976 album *Early Summer* and *Ryo Fukui in New York* as examples, but feel free to add your own. It is recommended that you add an album whose release date falls outside of the default range of 1993-2024.

Step 1: Opening album-rankings.csv

* In RStudio, go to *File* \-\> *Open File.* Open *data*. Inside will be a text file called *album-rankings.csv*. Open the file  
* Alternatively, you can choose to open *album-rankings.csv* directly with your OS’s native text editor (Notepad for Windows). The following steps will still work

Step 2: Adding your own album entry

* You will notice a list of album entries in this format:

  *Year,Ranking,Album,Artist,Rating,Vinyl,EP,Live*

* Enter your album entry according to the above format. To leave a field empty, press the comma key. It should look like this


* It is recommended to enter your album entries in chronological and hierarchical order. Although MFA’s user interface automatically detects rankings and sorts bands/artists in alphabetical order, this may make editing album entries in the future more difficult


  


  


  Bands and Artists tab with new entries


* Save your changes

You may notice that the slider and graph for MFA are limited to the years 1993-2024. For these MFA functions to reflect an album entry that falls outside of these years, alterations will have to be made

Step 3: Editing the slider function 

* In RStudio, go to *File* \-\> *Open File*. Open *app\_ui.*R  
* On line 24 of the code, you will see “*sliderInput*” along with MFA’s default values  
  * *‘value \= c(1993, 2024)’* represents the default range that MFA displays when the application starts up  
  * *‘min \= 1993, max \= 2024’* represents the minimum and maximum years that can be represented by the slider  
* Change the values to reflect your desired range. It should look like this

* Save your changes. The slider should now reflect your new album entry


  
Step 4: Editing the graphing function

* In RStudio, go to *File* \-\> *Open File.* Open *compare\_bands.R*  
* In lines 17 and 19, you will see brackets containing the similar default values of 1993, 2024  
* Change the values to reflect your desired range. However, on line 17, you will notice an additional field with a default value of 1\. This represents the scale of the X-axis on the graph. For this tutorial, this value will be changed to 5\.

## Adding Genres

This section will walk you through adding a simple genre function to MFA. We will similarly be using the same Ryo Fukui albums used in the previous tutorial.

Step 1: Opening album-rankings.csv

* In RStudio, go to *File* \-\> *Open File.* Open *data*. Inside will be a text file called *album-rankings.csv*. Open the file  
* Alternatively, you can choose to open *album-rankings.csv* directly with your OS’s native text editor (Notepad for Windows). The following steps will still work

Step 2: Modifying album entries

* Take a look again at the format of the album entries:  
  *Year,Ranking,Album,Artist,Rating,Vinyl,EP,Live*  
  Each of these can be seen to represent a column of information. We will be adding *Genre* for this tutorial, but any category you want to see reflected in MFA can be substituted.  
* At the top of *album-rankings.csv,* add *Genre* to the list of categories by adding a comma, and typing *Genre.* It should look like this  
  *Year,Ranking,Album,Artist,Rating,Vinyl,EP,Live,Genre*  
* Modify any existing album entries to include our new category. For us, that looks like

  *1976,1,Early Summer,Ryo Fukui,7,,,,Jazz*

  *1999,21,Ryo Fukui in New York,Ryo Fukui,9,,,,Jazz*

Step 3: Display your new category

* In RStudio, go to *File* \-\> *Open File.* Select both *albums\_by\_band.R* and *number\_one\_albums.R*  
    
* In *number\_one\_albums.R,* the line of code we are interested in modifying is line 7\. Like the csv file, add *Genre* towards the list of categories. It should look like this

* In *albums\_by\_band.R,* the line of code we are interested in is on line 13\. Repeat the previous instruction. It should look like this  
    
    
* MFA should now display a new genre column in the tabs that you’ve modified
